ce:section.ce:para:
In many reports about the application of MIP, toxicity or biocompatibility experiments have been performed [75,81]. Asadi et al. designed a biodegradable nano-structured molecularly imprinted polymer. In their study, except to the physi-chemical properties and in vivo performance, the biocompatibility of the prepared MIP was investigated. By cell viability test using human embryonic kidney (HEK293) over a period of three days, MIP was firmly proved to be harmless to live cell both in the visual observation of morphology and quantitative MTT assay test [52]. Mier et al. investigated the effect of MIP on the viability and irritation potential of human epithelial cells, which has proved its efficacy as an active agent to suppress body odors in cosmetic formulations. The thoroughly assessment showed that MIP did not affect bacterial growth when cultured in liquid media, suggesting that MIP would not affect the skin flora, which protects the body from dangerous pathogens. And the MIP displayed good biocompatibility in vitro toxicological study. All the results laid a foundation for the application of MIP in cosmetic or pharmaceutical formulations [82] (Fig. 5
                        ). FH-MIPNPs have low bio-toxicity through toxicity experiments in vitro and in vivo 
                        [43]. And Li, et al also proved the MIP showing the good biodegradable properties in the simulated physiological environment system [83]. All the studies suggested that MIP was a promising drug carrier with biocompatibility and biodegradability.
